    "content": "Here is the SEO-optimized article about 5 Exciting Additions in Rayman Legends Retold for Switch 2, crafted to meet your specific requirements.\n\n---\n\n# 5 Exciting Additions in Rayman Legends Retold for Switch 2\n\nThe rumor mill is spinning at full speed, and for good reason. With the anticipated release of the Nintendo Switch 2, fans are speculating about which classic titles will get the \"next-gen\" treatment. While many hope for sprawling, dark fantasy worlds, one of the most exciting prospects is a re-release of the best 2D platformer of the last decade: Rayman Legends Retold. While the original Rayman Legends remains a masterpiece of rhythm and animation, a \"Retold\" edition for the Switch 2 could revolutionize the experience. For players who love the tight controls and action-packed gameplay of platformers, this is a dream come true.\n\nWhile we wait for official news, here are 5 Exciting Additions in Rayman Legends Retold for Switch 2 that would make it the definitive way to play.\n\n## 1. Revamped Multiplayer & Co-op Modes\n\nThe original Rayman Legends was famous for its chaotic 4-player local co-op. However, a Switch 2 version could take this to the next level with robust online matchmaking. Imagine seamlessly dropping into a level with friends across the globe. Furthermore, new competitive \"Kung Foot\" tournaments could be expanded, making this one of the best Massively Multiplayer, RPG experiences in the platforming genre. For fans of online mayhem, this update would be a massive step forward. If you enjoy this style of chaotic multiplayer, you should also check out the best available action RPGs like Blade & Bones, which offers a different but equally thrilling cooperative challenge. You can find more about that game here: [best Action, Adventure games](https://pcgamearchive.com/en/game/blade-bones).\n\n## 2. Exclusive \"Murphy\" Touchscreen Improvements on Switch 2\n\nOne of the biggest complaints about the original Switch version of Rayman Legends was the reliance on the touchscreen for Murphy's stages, which felt clunky in docked mode. With the Switch 2’s upgraded hardware and potentially enhanced touch controls or gyroscopic aiming, this could be completely reworked. Rayman Legends Retold could offer a seamless hybrid experience where Murphy’s sections feel just as fluid with Pro Controller analog sticks as they do with touch. This upgrade would put it alongside other top-tier Action, Adventure games that redefine hardware use.\n\n## 3. A \"Legends+\" Expansion: New Levels & Worlds\n\nLet’s face it: while the base game has hundreds of levels, players crave more. A \"Retold\" edition simply must include a Legends+ expansion. This could feature brand-new musical levels timed to classic rock anthems or entirely new worlds drawn from the \"Rayman Origins\" art style. This addition alone would make it the definitive version of the game, offering content that rivals the depth of story-driven titles. If you are a fan of rich narratives and new worlds, you might also enjoy the epic scope of Forgotten Realms: Demon Stone, a fantastic Action, RPG game that delivers a deep dungeon-crawling experience. Explore that title here: [best Action, RPG games](https://pcgamearchive.com/en/game/forgotten-realms-demon-stone).\n\n## 4. Enhanced Visuals & 120FPS Performance\n\nThe original Rayman Legends was a visual stunner, utilizing the UbiArt Framework to look like a playable cartoon. A Switch 2 port could push this to the limit. Expect native 4K resolution in docked mode and silky-smooth 120 FPS gameplay. This would make the \"Invasion\" levels (which flash between two visual styles) incredibly immersive. The sheer fluidity of movement in a game like this is crucial, similar to how performance defines other high-octane titles in the genre. For another game that relies heavily on immersive worlds and performance, fans of the STAR WARS universe will find a similar sense of wonder. You can see how that franchise handles its action here: [best Massively Multiplayer, RPG games](https://pcgamearchive.com/en/game/star-wars).\n\n## 5. Deep Character Customization & Progression\n\nWhile Rayman Legends was largely a linear experience, the \"Retold\" version could introduce RPG-lite mechanics. Imagine unlocking distinct costumes not just as skins, but which grant slight gameplay buffs (e.g., a faster slide, a higher jump, or a splash damage attack). Rayman Legends Retold could feature a \"Progression Pass\" (free, of course) that rewards players for collecting Lums with skill trees. This would add replayability for players who have 100% the original game. For those who love deep character customization, the ultimate open-world standard remains X, which offers unparalleled freedom in building your hero. Check out that epic adventure here: [best Massively Multiplayer, RPG games](https://pcgamearchive.com/en/game/x).\n\n## Why You Should Play Rayman Legends Retold\n\nWhether these specific additions are confirmed or not, Rayman Legends Retold represents the pinnacle of platforming. The music is perfect, the controls are tight, and the art style is timeless. A Switch 2 version would bring this masterpiece to a new generation of gamers, cementing its legacy as a must-have launch title.\n\n### System Requirements (Speculative for Switch 2 Hardware)\n- Resolution: Up to 4K (Docked) / 1080p (Handheld)\n- Frame Rate: Target 120 FPS (Performance Mode) / 60 FPS (Graphics Mode)\n- Storage: Approx. 15-20 GB (Including Expansion Pack)\n- Online: Required for Online Co-op and Leaderboards\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe potential for 5 Exciting Additions in Rayman Legends Retold for Switch 2 is incredibly high. From revamped multiplayer to visual overhauls, this could be the definitive version of a classic. While we wait for Nintendo to reveal their next console, now is the perfect time to revisit the original game or check out some of the other incredible titles we’ve linked above.\n\nAre you excited for Rayman on the Switch 2? Let us know in the comments below!"
